WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.730 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, D.C.,

00:00:23.050 --> 00:00:24.350
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon and welcome

00:00:24.350 --> 00:00:26.670
to the African American
[inaudible] Division.

00:00:26.670 --> 00:00:30.330
I am Mary Jane Deeb, Chief of
the Division, and I'm delighted

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:35.020
to see you all here to attend
this special presentation

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:39.490
with Harry Boonin, who will
talk to us about his new book,

00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:42.520
Never Tell a Boy Not to Fight.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:48.930
As I always do, I make a little
presentation about our division,

00:00:48.930 --> 00:00:54.600
and our division is made up of
three sections, the African,

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:56.850
the Near East, and
the Hebraic Sections.

00:00:56.850 --> 00:01:02.250
We are responsible for materials
from 78 countries in the Near East,

00:01:02.250 --> 00:01:06.200
Central Asia, the Caucuses, and
well as from the entire continent

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:09.650
of Africa, north and
south sub-Sahara,

00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:12.630
and for the Hebraic
section we collect materials

00:01:12.630 --> 00:01:14.660
from all over the world.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:19.650
We are also very active
in acquiring materials,

00:01:19.650 --> 00:01:24.320
and restore our materials,
we develop our collections,

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:29.480
we brief our visitors, and
we serve the collections

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:32.290
in this reading room.

00:01:32.290 --> 00:01:37.690
We also invite scholars, and
experts, who have done research

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:42.990
and used our collections to share
their insights and their findings

00:01:42.990 --> 00:01:49.310
with our patrons, with
our audiences here

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:54.540
in the United States,
and across the world.

00:01:54.540 --> 00:02:00.550
And we like to have especially
authors who have written new books

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:06.590
and done research, to share, not
only the content of their research,

00:02:06.590 --> 00:02:09.160 position:56%
but how they've done their research.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.460
So we are particularly happy
to welcome Harry Boonin today,

00:02:12.460 --> 00:02:16.780
because he is making a presentation
on a topic that we rarely,

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:18.680
if ever, discuss at the Library.

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:20.570
Namely, boxing.

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:24.790
But Harry Boonin is a local
historian from Philadelphia,

00:02:24.790 --> 00:02:29.380 position:56%
whose work is, in many ways, unique,
as it focuses on boxers who came

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:32.100
from the Jewish Quarter
of Philadelphia.

00:02:32.100 --> 00:02:34.550
As I looked Harry up on Google,

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:37.760
I found a little announcement
about this project.

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.710
That was before the
book had been written,

00:02:40.710 --> 00:02:45.160 position:56%
where he introduces himself, and
then adds, "I'm looking for stories,

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:49.820
letters, diaries, photographs of
the lesser known Jewish fighters,

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:55.060
managers, such as Phil Glassman,
Boo Boo Hoff, love the name,

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:58.920
trainers such as Kudel
Seinfeld, and sports writers,

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:01.530
such as Lou Jaffe, of Philadelphia.

00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:03.990
Any personal stories
or personal content

00:03:03.990 --> 00:03:07.040
to families would be
greatly appreciated.

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:09.510
The moment you read this,
you really are excited.

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:12.050
You want to know-did
people give the letters?

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:14.130
Did they share their photographs?

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:16.710
You know, who are the
people, the stories?

00:03:16.710 --> 00:03:21.320
I mean it's a hook that immediately
makes you want to read the book,

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:24.410
and to know how that
book got written.

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:29.350
So I am sure he is going to share
with us a history and the story

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:32.440
of the boxer that he
is writing about.

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:36.860 position:56%
But now, our very own Sharon
Horowitz, Senior Reference Librarian

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.200
in The Hebraic Section will
introduce Harry Boonin,

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:41.540
and the program.

00:03:41.540 --> 00:03:43.510
So thank you.

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:48.180
[ Applause ]

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:49.850
&gt;&gt; Thank you Mary-Jane.

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:53.380
On behalf of the Hebraic
section, let me thank you all

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:55.680
for coming to today's program.

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:56.980
My name is Sharon Horowitz,

00:03:56.980 --> 00:03:59.980
I'm the reference librarian
in the Hebraic Section.

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:05.290
The Hebraic Section marks its
beginning in 1912, with the receipt

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:07.600
of 10,000 Hebrew books
and pamphlets,

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:10.130
whose purchase was
made possible by a gift

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:13.260
from a New York Philanthropist,
Jacob Schiff,

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:14.780
from those humble beginnings,

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:18.810
our collections have grown
to around 250,000 items.

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:22.350
In Hebrew, Yiddish,
Ladino, Judeo-Persian,

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:25.300
and other Hebraic script languages.

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:29.090
The Hebraic section also includes
an important collection of books

00:04:29.090 --> 00:04:32.360
in the languages of Gez,
Amharic, and Tigrinya,

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:36.070
languages of Ethiopia,
past and present.

00:04:36.070 --> 00:04:39.040
Our section's holdings
are particularly strong

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:44.160
in the subject areas of Bible and
Rabbinic liturgy, Hebrew language,

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.250
and literature response
and Jewish history.

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:50.660 position:56%
Two of our missions in this division
are to publicize our collections,

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:52.500
and to bring people
into the library,

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:56.710
and one way we accomplish this
second goal is by holding lectures,

00:04:56.710 --> 00:05:01.780 position:56%
and having programs, such as the one
we are hosting here today, and now,

00:05:01.780 --> 00:05:05.310
a word about our speaker, Mr.
Harry Boonin, who received his B.A.

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:10.000 position:56%
from Pennsylvania State University
and his J.D. from Temple University.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:15.580 position:56%
Before retiring, he worked for many
years as a lawyer for the U.S. Navy.

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:19.130
Mr. Boonin devotes much of
his time to Jewish genealogy

00:05:19.130 --> 00:05:21.920
and to Philadelphia Jewish history.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.360
He was the founding President
of the Jewish Genealogy Society

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:28.550
of greater Philadelphia, editor of
their newsletter, and was honored

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:32.360
by the Society for
Lifetime Dedication.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:34.100
Harry has published many articles

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:37.230
in the Jewish Genealogy
Journal of [inaudible].

00:05:37.230 --> 00:05:40.720
The book we will hear
about today is his fourth.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:44.050
Never Tell a Boy Not to Fight
describes the lost world

00:05:44.050 --> 00:05:47.730
of Philadelphia Jewish boxing, and
the story of immigrant Jewish boys

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:52.350
who literally fought
their way up from poverty.

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:55.630
One item of business, before
we hear from Mr. Boonin,

00:05:55.630 --> 00:06:00.140
this event is being videotaped
for subsequent broadcasting.

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:03.220
There will be a formal question and
answer period after the lecture,

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:04.940
at which time the audience
is encouraged

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:07.840 position:56%
to ask questions and offer comments.

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:11.700
Please be advised that your
voice and image may be recorded

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:14.900
and later broadcast
as part of this event.

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:18.210 position:56%
By participating in the question and
answer period, you are consenting

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:20.760
to the library's possible
reproduction

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.850
and transmission of your remarks.

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:26.570
And now, please join me in
welcoming Mr. Harry Boonin.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:33.610
Oh, one more thing-there are
questionnaires asking for feedback

00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:34.930
that are going to be distributed.

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:37.170
If not on your chair, they will be.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.860
So if you could fill them out and
hand them in before you leave,

00:06:40.860 --> 00:06:46.200
that would be appreciated, and
also the book, Never Tell a Boy Not

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:50.030
to Fight is for sale in the back,
and Mr. Boonin will be very happy

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:51.650
to sign them if anybody wants.

00:06:51.650 --> 00:06:54.510
Thank you.

00:06:54.510 --> 00:06:59.170
[ Applause ]

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:06.090
&gt;&gt; Thank you for the very nice
introductions, and welcome,

00:07:06.090 --> 00:07:08.770
you all, on such a beautiful day.

00:07:08.770 --> 00:07:11.790
A question about letters
has been brought up,

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:14.410
whether I ever got any letters.

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:19.180
Well, that shows you how little I
knew when I started about boxers.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:23.260
Boxers wear eight ounce gloves, and
I guess they can't write letters

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:27.600
with their gloves on [laughs],
but boxers do not write letters,

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:32.450
which is a big disappointment, if
any of you want to be a biographer,

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:34.060
make sure that the
person you're writing

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.900
about writes letters,
or writes something.

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:40.400
It's difficult without
them, without the diary.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.770
How did I get into this?

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:47.600 position:56%
Twenty-four years ago, I was working
for the Navy, and I found myself

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:53.010
in London one day, London,
England, and I had a few hours off.

00:07:53.010 --> 00:07:59.660
And I decided to take a walking
tour of the old east end of London.

00:07:59.660 --> 00:08:01.000
It was a wonderful tour.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.820
I thought I would do the same thing
when I came back to Philadelphia.

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:06.120
Nobody was doing it.

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:09.760
I started them, and I
did it for 15 years.

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:13.490
And what came out of it was a
book called The Jewish Quarter

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:14.840
of Philadelphia.

00:08:14.840 --> 00:08:17.510
And when I finished the
book, I was frustrated

00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:21.520
because I felt I really
hadn't told the full story

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:26.520
of the Jewish Quarter, and the
Russian Jews who settled there.

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:29.650
So I wrote a second book,
about a Synagogue of the area,

00:08:29.650 --> 00:08:38.710 position:56%
and the synagogue, I was surprised
to find, had parents, three parents,

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:42.280
that had sons who were
professional boxers.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:47.450
And I though that was odd, whether
it was or not, I'm not sure.

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:52.090
Then I found out that one of
the premiere boxing managers

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:55.490
in Philadelphia was also
a member of the synagogue.

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:58.190
So I finished the synagogue
book, and I thought I was done,

00:08:58.190 --> 00:09:02.580
but the boxers fascinated me.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:04.490
I was intrigued.

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:06.820
And I thought I would do
a little bit of research,

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:11.700
and see if there was a possibility
that a book could be written.

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:17.440
I found out that Philadelphia,
a century ago,

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:21.900
had many dozen professional boxers.

00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:29.040
In 1928, there were more
Jewish boxers for an ethnicity

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:33.380
than any other ethnicity
in the United States.

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:37.360
It only lasted a short time, and
I guess that put me over the top.

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:41.490
And I said, well, I guess
three books make a trilogy,

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:43.230
and I started on my boxing book.

00:09:43.230 --> 00:09:44.970
It took eight years.

00:09:44.970 --> 00:09:49.110
And this is basically the story.

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:52.420
Let me get started.

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:57.970
This photograph comes from
the Library of Congress,

00:09:57.970 --> 00:10:04.020
and it is from the Association
of Newsboys, from Cincinnati.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:07.220
It's a very interesting
picture, for many reasons.

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:16.710
A lot of the Jewish newsboys in
Philadelphia were not lucky enough

00:10:16.710 --> 00:10:20.070
to have any kind of training
like this, but this seems

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:22.240
to be, to be a training room.

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:24.710
The boys, some of the boys
you'll see, are in bare feet.

00:10:24.710 --> 00:10:27.770
Other boys have shoes on.

00:10:27.770 --> 00:10:31.860
You'll notice, there's
no adults in the room.

00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:35.010
And the boys are learning
from each other.

00:10:35.010 --> 00:10:37.940
The remarkable part
about this picture is,

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:41.800
if there are both African
American and white boys together,

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:47.730
and they seem, from the picture,
to have been getting along,

00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:53.140
and learning, and concentrating,
despite all of the prejudice

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:56.580
that existed around
them at that time.

00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:02.260 position:56%
In fact, if you'll look on the
right-hand side of your screen, I...

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:10.560
[ Inaudible ]

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:17.360
&gt;&gt; There is a-one of the larger
boys, is standing next to,

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:21.440
on his right, a white boy,
and he has his hand gently

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.160
on the boy's shoulder,
and you can see

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:28.690
from this little fact,
how close the boys were.

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:31.530
They were intently, and
you can see in their eyes,

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:34.260
how intently they are in learning.

00:11:37.310 --> 00:11:39.070
This next picture comes
from Philadelphia,

00:11:39.070 --> 00:11:42.800
and again involves the boys.

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:46.560
Newsboys, a lot of Jews
were newsboys at that time.

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:51.910
I was unable to find any kind of
study in Philadelphia, Cincinnati,

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:55.540
or New York, but I did find a
study of newsboys in Denver,

00:11:55.540 --> 00:11:58.410
Colorado, a few years later.

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:02.160
And of the 250 newsboys
that were studied,

00:12:02.160 --> 00:12:06.260
125 or half of them were Jewish,

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:10.190
which I found really
surprising in Denver, Colorado.

00:12:10.190 --> 00:12:14.480
This particular picture
shows, on the left-hand side,

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:17.030
you'll see there's a girl
on a swing, and if you look

00:12:17.030 --> 00:12:19.500
in the middle, in the back,
there's a single girl,

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:22.690
who is reading a book, but in
the front, there are two boys,

00:12:22.690 --> 00:12:27.760
who are practicing the art of
boxing, the manly art of boxing,

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:31.270
and the teacher doesn't seem
to be interfering with them.

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:32.570
She's letting it go.

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:36.100
So this was something today,
you would see a baseball game,

00:12:36.100 --> 00:12:38.330
maybe the kids are playing
ball against the wall,

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:41.010
but what is what the
kids practiced then.

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:51.390 position:56%
To get into boxing, in Philadelphia,
which is probably like all the towns

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:54.000
in the eastern part
of the United States,

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.860
one of the most unusual
venues was called a cyclorama.

00:12:58.860 --> 00:13:00.550
And the picture of it is here.

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:04.170
This picture is stated
it was taken in 1887,

00:13:04.170 --> 00:13:07.940
and this is where the first
Jewish fighter fought.

00:13:07.940 --> 00:13:13.350
A cyclorama is a painting
that is mounted on the inside

00:13:13.350 --> 00:13:16.710
of a round building, the
battle of Gettysburg is one

00:13:16.710 --> 00:13:21.650 position:56%
of the most popular cycloramas after
the Civil War, and you can see it

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:25.820
if you go-has anybody here
gone to the Gettysburg Museum?

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.560
The new museum opened up.

00:13:27.560 --> 00:13:29.730
They have a cyclorama up there.

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:35.560
And it has 20,000-20,000
life-sized figures.

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:41.930
The building on the right
is the same building,

00:13:41.930 --> 00:13:46.590
it's painted white here, it's
called the Winter Circus.

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:49.260
This was converted
from the cyclorama

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:53.310
to the Winter Circus
for boxing in 1893.

00:13:53.310 --> 00:13:55.380
First, there were Vaudeville
shows here,

00:13:55.380 --> 00:14:06.020
and after the Vaudeville shows,
the interest wanted in the city,

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:14.150
and the manager thought he
would try to bring in boxing.

00:14:14.150 --> 00:14:21.190
One of the boxers he
brought in was Jewish.

00:14:21.190 --> 00:14:23.430
This is a famous painting.

00:14:23.430 --> 00:14:27.300
You may recognize the
painting by Thomas Eakins.

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:32.350
Eakins painted it in 1898,

00:14:32.350 --> 00:14:36.100
and it was in the interior
of the same building.

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:39.840
You can see in this painting
on the left-hand side,

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:44.360
you'll see there's a press
box, right above the policeman

00:14:44.360 --> 00:14:49.900
who is standing there, in the
press box were three journalists,

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.180
I guess you'd call
them sports writers,

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:56.380
although they didn't really call
them sports writers at that time,

00:14:56.380 --> 00:15:01.180
because it wasn't a profession,
and a fellow that named the round,

00:15:01.180 --> 00:15:03.270
and then they also had
a telegraph operator.

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:06.990 position:56%
So if you were a boxing manager, and
you wanted to get your story out,

00:15:06.990 --> 00:15:08.910
you didn't have to go
to a telegraph office,

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:11.730
you could do it right
from the boxing arena.

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:17.550
The fellow in the foreground is
the timekeeper, and you can see

00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:21.400
that the ropes in the
ring are already a foot

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:27.790
or more inside the raised
platform that they fought on.

00:15:27.790 --> 00:15:31.600 position:56%
So if the fellow was knocked through
the ropes, he didn't fall right away

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:36.590 position:56%
onto the floor, which is quite a
fall, but he would fall on the edge,

00:15:36.590 --> 00:15:39.740
and hopefully stay
within the platform.

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:44.280
This is a fellow, that is Henry
Pinkus [assumed spelling],

00:15:44.280 --> 00:15:48.150
who was the first promoter
at the Winter Circus.

00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:55.720
He was also an inventor, filed six
patents at the Library of Congress,

00:15:55.720 --> 00:16:02.170
and remained in the fight game
until he ended up being arrested.

00:16:02.170 --> 00:16:09.090 position:56%
In 1898, the fight game was still
considered semi-legal in some towns,

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:13.390
and completely illegal in others.

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:19.880
He finally had enough, and he
left Philadelphia for New York.

00:16:21.230 --> 00:16:25.020
This is a picture of the
first Jewish fighter.

00:16:25.020 --> 00:16:27.640
He had 60 professional
Jewish fights.

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:32.500
He fought from 1893 to 1905.

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:34.990
His name was Izzy Strauss.

00:16:34.990 --> 00:16:39.360
But they called him
the Hebrew Cyclone.

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:47.100
Both of those words would have been
a surprise to the boxing public

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:48.940
